production in children with

In the summer of 2017, I took an incredible class called
Interactivity, in which I befriended classmates from all over
the world. Most of them were international students studying
abroad from other continents, and all have faced some form
of language barrier.
Getting to know their stories reminded me of my own
transitional experience as an immigrant. Taking inspiration
from their lives, I created a second-language learning
application for children for my final project - and my
classmates loved it. This encouraged me to further research
the topic from both design and linguistics perspectives, and
create redesigns, which will be elaborated on in the following
case study.
BACKGROUND
ORIGINAL PRODUCT
I wrote the original project in Javascript using a client-side
library called p5.js, its speech recognition/synthesis library,
and spirits character library. These modules provided helpful
APIs that powered the product interface:
A voice UI that responds to spoken words
A user is triggered by the selection tool, selects a character,
then responds to a synthesized prompt asking ‚ÄúCan you say
‚Äòcharacter name‚Äô‚Äù to obtain the character.
Interactive, visually-attractive components
The p5.spirits library allowed each character to define its own
lifespan, animation, and behavior. I uploaded frames of each
character to give them animated interactions with the user.

CURRICULUM EVALUATION
In order to design for learners, I must first
understand how they learn.
When I first immigrated, I learned English not only through
reading children‚Äôs books and watching TV, but also through
interacting with my outer environment. However, despite
having been intended for a younger age group, the original
curriculum was built on assumptions based on my past.
I knew that the current method may not be mature enough
for the purpose of language learning, and I wanted to
explore, in particular, how children between the age of 1.5-5
years learn language. In response, I enrolled in a child
language development class under Professor Nina Hyams,
one of the leading figures in child language acquisition
theory. Here is what I learned:
1. A child acquiring their second language (L2), undergo
the same process as the native speaker children of that
language.
2. The average child understands more words than he can
produce, and may produce words differently.
3. Explicitly correcting a child‚Äôs product (negative evidence)
usually has little influence on his/her rate of learning.
4. Children prefer simple one-to-one mapping for labels,
and thus assume that each object has one and only one
label.
5. Children use syntactic frames (properties of syntax) to
infer word meaning, especially verb meaning.
6. when a child has acquired the initial 50 words, there will
be an explosion (spurt) in his/her word learning.
7. A child‚Äôs linguistic level can be measured by his/her
average number of verbs ormeaningful units in his
utterance.
Based on these findings, I proceeded to make product feature
revisions for my redesign.
PARTICIPATORY FEEDBACK
Based on their opinions, I reached the following conclusions:
The current voice recognition model may be
too strict for language-learners.
Learners, especially children, can be discouraged in the
process of repeating the same word. The importance of
paralinguistic features must be harmonized with learning
goals to grant the users with more gratification.
Textual onboarding was not enough - users
needed more demonstrative guides.
Voice UIs have yet to become so popular as to be intuitive for
the common user. Thus, it was very important that they are
comfortable with the app‚Äôs interactions before beginning to
use its features on a blank canvas.
The curriculum needed to be tailored with an
understanding of how children learn language.

PRODUCT DECISIONS
The goal is to encourage children to interact
(speak and listen) with the characters for fun
and meaningful linguistic exposure.
Based on user research and curriculum evaluation, I decided
to include the following features that would provide the most
value for children learning English and their guardians:
‚Ä¢ Onboarding screen with an option for first time users to
immediately engage with the voice interface
Different modules for parts of speech ordered by
difficulty
‚Ä¢ New speech recognition algorithm to accept child
productions that range in their phonemic resemblence
Because the visual components have already
received positive feedback, I crafted new
features consistent with my original design.

The new onboarding page
Functional icons were used to illustrate
actions and help the user understand
the upcoming procedure. The
onboarding component is targeted
towards parents and guardians, who
will be physically guiding the child
through the interface.
A child-centered curriculum
Children acquire nouns more easily and
later use these to syntactically
boostrap their verb and proposition
learning. Drawing from this, I designed
the curriculum to begin with common
nouns, then process onto more
advanced parts of speech. This lowers
the learning curve for children.
Know your child‚Äôs progress
I added a green progress bar on the
bottom of the page to indicate the
current learning stage of the child, to
help guardians keep track of their
progress.
The design of the progress bar fits in
seamlessly with the meadow-and-blue-
sky design language.
Pronunciation is not
necessarily key, but I‚Äôll let you
decide that.
When setting the voice recognition
algorithm standards, we recommend
guardians to relax the phonemic
demand if the child‚Äôs pronunciation has
yet to be adult-like. We will also
provide a recommendation for a
setting based on the child‚Äôs progress.

FINAL THOUGHTS
Longitudinal studies are needed to evaluate
the effectiveness of this application.
After the first round of usability testing and theoretical
validation, I‚Äôm interested in whether this incenticization
technique will actually help ESL children practice their word
production. A possible evaluation would be to provide a
controlled period of access to a group of ESL children with no
exposure to English, then measuring their growth using MLU
and VSU metrics as they voluntarily engage with the game
over some number of months.
Some parts of the user journey can be
improved through more automation.
For example, the voice recognition threshold can be reduced
to an automatic process through storing the latest session
which the child has played the game, and the number of
accurate pronunciations per session. From this, we can
deduce an approperiate amount to increase for the threshold,
and adjust it based on next session‚Äôs accuracy.
Similarly, if a child has demonstrated outstanding fluency in a
basic module, we can recommend a harder module to see if
the curriculum can be fast-forwarded.
Thank you for reading!
